# AI Agent Instructions

## Communication Style
- Be concise and direct
- Minimal preamble or postamble
- Save details for unfinished tasks or next steps, not accomplishments
- Answer exactly what's asked, nothing more

## Documentation Rules
- Keep dev logs high-level (what we worked on, not how); do not overmention trivial or silly details
- Track open conversations, unfinished work, and blockers
- All details go in docs/context.txt, not in dev logs
- Before committing: recalculate and resummarize today's devlog entry (do not just append); one concise summary of the day
- Devlog update goes in the same commit as the changes being documented

## File Management
- NEVER create files unless absolutely necessary
- ALWAYS prefer editing existing files over creating new ones
- NEVER proactively create documentation or README files unless explicitly requested

## Questions
- Ask maximum 2 questions at a time
- Track open conversations in docs/context.txt so nothing is forgotten

## Project Structure
- Dev logs: docs/devlogs/v1.txt (will split by version if needed)
- Context file: docs/context.txt (current project status, open items, project-specific info - NOT AI behavior rules)
- Requirements: docs/requirements.md (tree structure: features → use cases with checkboxes)
- Frontend tree: docs/frontend-tree.md (source of truth for src/ atoms, layouts, pages); update it in the same commit when changing frontend structure
- Design: docs/design.md (colour palette and design rules; logo-derived, use with hierarchy)

## File Updates & Confirmations
- When user requests new AI behaviors/workflows → proactively detect and propose adding to .aidescription, ask confirmation first
- When adding to docs/context.txt → ask confirmation first on what will be added
- Detect when user describes new rules/behaviors and offer to document them
- Do not implement features or UI that are not in docs/requirements.md without asking first
- For large or multi-step changes, propose the steps and get confirmation before proceeding
- Do not add new npm dependencies without asking

## File Formats & Examples

### docs/requirements.md
Tree structure: features → use cases with checkboxes
- Finalized feature decisions with checkboxes
- Draft/undecided features marked with [DRAFT] prefix
- [DRAFT] items also remain in docs/context.txt "Open Conversations"

Example:
## Version 1

### Feature: User Authentication
- [ ] User can sign up with email
- [ ] User can log in
  - [ ] Remember me option
- [ ] User can reset password

### Feature: [DRAFT] Social Login
- [ ] Login with Google
- [ ] Login with Facebook

### docs/devlogs/v*.txt
Daily entries, high-level accomplishments only
Example:
## 2026-01-06

### What We Accomplished
- Set up project structure

### What's Unfinished
- Define app requirements
- Build authentication flow

### docs/context.txt
Sections: Open Conversations, Restrictions, Requirements, Bugs
- Open/undecided decisions and discussions
- [DRAFT] requirements from requirements.md
- Current project status and next steps
Keep concise, track current project state only

## Code Standards

### Naming Conventions
- Variables/functions: camelCase
- Components/classes: PascalCase
- Event handlers: use `on` prefix (e.g., onClick, onSubmit)

### File Organization
- One component per file; component filename matches component name (PascalCase)
- Atoms, layouts, pages, and contexts: one per folder with `index.ts`; contexts must have co-located `.test.tsx` (same as atoms/layouts)
- Always update docs/frontend-tree.md when adding, removing, or renaming under src/. In the tree, do not list files when the folder name already implies them (e.g. list `Button/` not the files inside)
- Before adding a new atom, layout, or context: check docs/frontend-tree.md and the codebase for an equivalent; if one might exist or overlap, ask the user for permission. Do not add without this check and explicit approval

### Code Quality
- No duplicated code - extract into reusable functions/components
- Always follow TDD: write or update the test first, then implement. Do not add a new atom, layout, or context without a co-located `.test.tsx` that passes
- Frequently check for test warnings: run tests and inspect stderr/console; fix or suppress expected warnings (e.g. React error boundaries) so the suite stays clean
- Refactor before committing
- Don't patch bugs - debug root cause and fix properly
- Clean, maintainable code over quick fixes

### Design
- Use colours from docs/design.md only; implement via CSS variables (light/dark). Do not introduce new colours outside the palette without asking

### Documentation & Explanations
- Explain what code does before committing
- Maintain architecture diagrams (UML or similar) showing how components/classes interact
- Maintain entity relationship diagram for database structure
- Maintain JSON Schema (docs/database-schema.json) for database validation
- Keep diagrams in docs/architecture/ folder
- Update docs/architecture/ when adding/changing major components or flows (contexts, shell, auth, routing)

### Translations
- User-facing strings: all text visible to the user (labels, buttons, headings, aria-labels, placeholders) must come from the translation function t(key) or from configurable data (e.g. company.currency, company.name from database). No raw literal strings in JSX for user-facing copy.
- When adding new UI copy, add the key to locale JSON (en first) and use t('key') in the component. Key naming: app.*, nav.*, auth.*, home.*, inventory.*, budget.*, etc.

### Clean code (must follow)
- Use Button atom for all buttons; no raw <button>. Use Input and Label atoms for form fields. Do not add one-off styled elements that duplicate atom behaviour.
- Export only what is needed (e.g. Provider + hook for contexts; the component for atoms). Keep helpers and internal constants non-exported.
- If two or more modules share the same pattern, either extract a shared helper or add a one-line comment stating why duplication is intentional.
- Change only what is required for the task. Do not refactor for clarity or style unless the user explicitly asks.
- Before commit: run tests; confirm no raw <button>/<input>/<label> where an atom exists and fits; if the change adds a context, shell, or routing structure, add or update a diagram in docs/architecture/ in the same commit.

## Git Workflow

### Before commit
- Run tests (must pass) before committing; check for test warnings (stderr/console) and fix or document them
- Run `npm run test:coverage` when touching tests or critical paths; coverage report in `coverage/` (see package.json scripts)
- Recalculate and resummarize today's devlog entry (concise, high-level; no trivial details); include it in the same commit

### After commit
- Always push after committing. Never leave code only on local; push to the remote (e.g. origin) so work is backed up and visible.

### Commit Message Format
Format: `type(scope): description`
- Type: `feat` or `fix`
- Scope: generic feature name in parentheses
- Description: complete the phrase "If applied, this commit will..."
  - Keep it short and imperative mood
  - Example: `feat(auth): add user login functionality`
  - Example: `fix(api): handle empty response errors`
- NEVER add "Generated with Claude Code" or "Co-Authored-By" footers
- Keep commit messages concise

